## What happened

**.NET 11 removed the OpenSSL back-end for DSA on macOS.** Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have never supported DSA, so in earlier .NET versions the runtime quietly used a bundled/system OpenSSL for DSA operations on macOS. In .NET 11, that OpenSSL fallback was dropped, making `DSA.Create()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS — the same thing that already happened on iOS/tvOS/macCatalyst in earlier releases.

Linux and Windows still work because they have native DSA support (OpenSSL and CNG, respectively).

## How to fix it

**Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for legacy verification)**

```csharp
// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)
{
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is a fully managed implementation — no platform-native dependency, works on all OSes.

**Option 2 — Migrate to a modern algorithm**

If you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, which are supported natively on all .NET platforms:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
```

## Recommendation

Since you're *verifying legacy signatures* (you can't re-sign old data), go with **Option 1** (BouncyCastle) for backward compatibility, and adopt ECDSA/Ed25519 for any new signing going forward.
